'''Rick Rivet''' (born 1949 in [[Aklavik]], [[Northwest Territories]]) is a [[Sahtu]]&ndash;[[Métis people (Canada)|Métis]] [[painter]] living in [[Canada]].

==Background and education==
Rivet's family lived both in the country and in town at Aklavik, which was a [[Métis]] trading center. Métis have a specific culture with [[First Nations]] and [[European ethnic groups|European]] roots. He began school in Aklavik at age seven.<ref name=bio>[http://www.rickrivet.ca/biography.php "About Rick Rivet."] ''Rick Rivet.''] 2014. Accessed 4 May 2014.</ref>

River earned four degrees: his Bachelor of Arts from the [[University of Alberta]] in 1972; his Bachelor of Fine Arts from the [[University of Victoria]] in 1980; his Master of Fine Arts from the [[University of Saskatchewan]] in 1985, and Bachelor of Education from the [[University of Saskatchewan]] in 1986.<ref name=bio/>

==Artwork==
His art is deeply influenced by ideas of fusion and hybridity of cultures.<ref>{{cite book|title=Contemporary Masters: The Eiteljorg Fellowship for Native American Fine Art, Vol. I|date=1999|publisher=Eiteljorg Museum of American Indians and Western Art|location=Indianapolis, IN|isbn=0-9635492-2-7|page=32}}</ref>  He works primarily in acrylic on canvas in a style he has referred to as "an expressionist/primitivist approach."<ref>{{cite book|last=Ostrowitz|first=Judith|title=Privileging the Past: Reconstructing History in Northwest Coast Art|date=1999|publisher=University of Washington Press|page=150}}</ref>

